>\u003Ch2>commentary\u003C/h2>  \u003Cp>δῶρον appears the most likely reading of the latter part of the text, but it is very difficult to judge whether one or more letters is missing between Δ and Ρ, and even if a letter is missing at all between Σ and Δ. From the photograph, it seems possible that the letter between Μ and Α could also be a Φ.\u003C/p>  \u003C/div>  \u003Cdiv id=\"bibliography\">\u003Ch2>bibliography\u003C/h2>  \u003Cul>\u003Cli> 28.0768 \u003Ca href=\"https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10000796\" target=\"_blank\">https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10000796\u003C/a>\u003C/li>\u003Cli> De Miro and Fiorentini 1976-1977 453 tav.48 fig.3 \u003Ca href=\"https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10002049\" target=\"_blank\">https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10002049\u003C/a>\u003C/li>\u003C/ul>  \u003Cul>\u003Cli>\u003C/li>\u003C/ul>  \u003C/div>  \u003Cdiv id=\"handnote\">\u003Cp>Small neat letters of square form. From the photograph, it appears the sigma may be fairly open, the alpha with straight bar, and the rho possibly with a tail.\u003C/p> Line 1    Interlineation line 1 to 2    \u003C/div>\u003Cdiv id=\"license\"> Licensed under a Creative Commons-Attribution 4.0 licence. \u003C/div>",[174,177,180,183,186,189,192,195],{"id":175,"html":176},"editions","\u003Cdiv class=\"attribution\">Text encoding: Jonathan Prag\u003C/div>\u003Cdiv id=\"edition-interpretive\" lang=\"grc\">  \u003Cdiv class=\"textpart\" lang=\"grc\">\u003Cspan class=\"ab\" id=\"div-interpretive\">  \u003Ca id=\"al1-interpretive\">\u003C!--0-->\u003C/a>\u003Cspan class=\"linenumber\">1\u003C/span>[\u003Cspan dir=\"ltr\" class=\"gap\">---\u003C/span>]ΜΙΑΣ[\u003Cspan dir=\"ltr\" class=\"gap\">.\u003C/span>]Δ[\u003Cspan dir=\"ltr\" class=\"gap\">.\u003C/span>]ΡΟΝ \u003C/span>\u003C/div>  \u003Cp class=\"miniapp\">\u003C/p>\u003C/div>\u003Cdiv class=\"attribution\">Text encoding: Jonathan Prag\u003C/div>\u003Cdiv id=\"edition-diplomatic\" lang=\"grc\">\u003Cdiv class=\"textpart\" lang